an style="font-family: MathJax_Size3;">(</span></span><span class="mfrac" id="MathJax-Span-64"><span style="display: inline-block; position: relative; width: 1.074em; height: 0px; margin-right: 0.12em; margin-left: 0.12em;"><span style="position: absolute; clip: rect(3.152em, 1000.94em, 4.178em, -1000em); top: -4.683em; left: 50%; margin-left: -0.477em;"><span class="mrow" id="MathJax-Span-65"><span class="mi" id="MathJax-Span-66" style="font-family: MathJax_Math-italic;">c</span><span class="mi" id="MathJax-Span-67" style="font-family: MathJax_Math-italic;">k</span></span><span style="display: inline-block; width: 0px; height: 4.006em;"></span></span><span style="position: absolute; clip: rect(3.403em, 1000.6em, 4.178em, -1000em); top: -3.32em; left: 50%; margin-left: -0.311em;"><span class="mi" id="MathJax-Span-68" style="font-family: MathJax_Math-italic;">Žē</span><span style="display: inline-block; width: 0px; height: 4.006em;"></span></span><span style="position: absolute; clip: rect(0.841em, 1001.07em, 1.229em, -1000em); top: -1.288em; left: 0em;"><span style="display: inline-block; overflow: hidden; vertical-align: 0em; border-top: 1.3px solid; width: 1.074em; height: 0px;"></span><span style="display: inline-block; width: 0px; height: 1.068em;"></span></span></span></span><span class="mo" id="MathJax-Span-69" style="vertical-align: 0em;"><span style="font-family: MathJax_Size3;">)</span></span></span><span style="display: inline-block; width: 0px; height: 4.006em;"></span></span><span style="position: absolute; top: -5.183em; left: 2.786em;"><span class="mn" id="MathJax-Span-70" style="font-size: 70.7%; font-family: MathJax_Main;">2</span><span style="display: inline-block; width: 0px; height: 4.006em;"></span></span></span></span></span><span style="display: inline-block; width: 0px; height: 2.19em;"></span></span></span><span style="display: inline-block; overflow: hidden; vertical-align: -1.173em; border-left: 0px solid; width: 0px; height: 3.163em;"></span></span></nobr><span class="MJX_Assistive_MathML MJX_Assistive_MathML_Block" role="presentation"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><mi>╬Ą</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>Žē</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>=</mo><msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>c</mi><mi>k</mi></mrow><mi>Žē</mi></mfrac><mo>)</mo></mrow><mn>2</mn></msup></math></span></span></div>
</p>
<p>We will then compare this with the analytical ╬Ą(Žē) that we specified. The simulation script is in <a href="https://github.com/NanoComp/meep/blob/master/python/examples/material-dispersion.py">material-dispersion.py</a>.</p>
<p>Since this is a uniform medium, our computational cell can actually be of <em>zero</em> size (i.e. one pixel), where we will use Bloch-periodic boundary conditions to specify the wavevector <em>k</em>.</p>
<pre><code class="language-py hljs language-python">cell = mp.Vector3()
resolution = <span class="hljs-number">20</span>
</code></pre>
<p>We will then fill all space with an artificial dispersive material:</p>
<pre><code class="language-py hljs language-python">susceptibilities = [mp.LorentzianSusceptibility(frequency=<span class="hljs-number">1.1</span>, gamma=<span class="hljs-number">1e-5</span>, sigma=<span class="hljs-number">0.5</span>),
                    mp.LorentzianSusceptibility(frequency=<span class="hljs-number">0.5</span>, gamma=<span class="hljs-number">0.1</span>, sigma=<span class="hljs-number">2e-5</span>)]

default_material = mp.Medium(epsilon=<span class="hljs-number">2.25</span>, E_susceptibilities=susceptibilities)
</code></pre>
<p>corresponding to the dielectric function:</p>
