-italic; padding-left: 0.222em;">i</span><span class="mi" id="MathJax-Span-142" style="font-family: MathJax_Math-italic;">f<span style="display: inline-block; overflow: hidden; height: 1px; width: 0.06em;"></span></span><span class="mo" id="MathJax-Span-143" style="font-family: MathJax_Main; padding-left: 0.222em;">Ōŗģ</span><span class="mn" id="MathJax-Span-144" style="font-family: MathJax_Main; padding-left: 0.222em;">0.1</span><span class="texatom" id="MathJax-Span-145"><span class="mrow" id="MathJax-Span-146"><span class="mo" id="MathJax-Span-147" style="font-family: MathJax_Main;">/</span></span></span><span class="mn" id="MathJax-Span-148" style="font-family: MathJax_Main;">2</span><span class="mi" id="MathJax-Span-149" style="font-family: MathJax_Math-italic;">ŽĆ<span style="display: inline-block; overflow: hidden; height: 1px; width: 0.003em;"></span></span></span><span style="display: inline-block; width: 0px; height: 4.006em;"></span></span><span style="position: absolute; clip: rect(0.841em, 1009.78em, 1.229em, -1000em); top: -1.288em; left: 0em;"><span style="display: inline-block; overflow: hidden; vertical-align: 0em; border-top: 1.3px solid; width: 9.785em; height: 0px;"></span><span style="display: inline-block; width: 0px; height: 1.068em;"></span></span></span></span></span><span style="display: inline-block; width: 0px; height: 2.19em;"></span></span></span><span style="display: inline-block; overflow: hidden; vertical-align: -1.335em; border-left: 0px solid; width: 0px; height: 3.2em;"></span></span></nobr><span class="MJX_Assistive_MathML MJX_Assistive_MathML_Block" role="presentation"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><mi>╬Ą</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>Žē</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mi>╬Ą</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>ŽĆ</mi><mi>f</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>2.25</mn><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mrow><msup><mn>1.1</mn><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>Ōŗģ</mo><mn>0.5</mn></mrow><mrow><msup><mn>1.1</mn><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>ŌłÆ</mo><msup><mi>f</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>ŌłÆ</mo><mi>i</mi><mi>f</mi><mo>Ōŗģ</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><mo>ŌłÆ</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup><mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><mo>/</mo></mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>ŽĆ</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mrow><msup><mn>0.5</mn><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>Ōŗģ</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>Ōŗģ</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><mo>ŌłÆ</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><msup><mn>0.5</mn><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>ŌłÆ</mo><msup><mi>f</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>ŌłÆ</mo><mi>i</mi><mi>f</mi><mo>Ōŗģ</mo><mn>0.1</mn><mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><mo>/</mo></mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>ŽĆ</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></span></span></div>
</p>
<p>The real and imaginary parts of this dielectric function ╬Ą(Žē) are plotted below:</p>
<p><img alt="" src="https://meep.readthedocs.io/en/master/images/Material-dispersion-eps.png#center"></p>
<p>We can see that the f=1.1 resonance causes a large change in both the real and imaginary parts of ╬Ą around that frequency. In fact, there is a range of frequencies from 1.1 to 1.2161 where ╬Ą is <em>negative</em>. In this range, no propagating modes exist ŌĆö it is actually a kind of electromagnetic band gap associated with polariton resonances in a material. For more information on the physics of such materials, see e.g. Chapter 14 of <a href="http://www.wiley.com/WileyCDA/WileyTitle/productCd-EHEP000803.html">Introduction to Solid State Physics</a> by C. Kittel.</p>
<p>On the other hand, the f=0.5 resonance, because the <code>sigma</code> numerator is so small, causes very little change in the real part of ╬Ą. Nevertheless, it generates a clear peak in the <em>imaginary</em> part of ╬Ą, corresponding to a resonant absorption peak.</p>
<p>Now, we'll set up the rest of the simulation. We'll specify a broadband <span class="MathJax_Preview" style="color: inherit; display: none;"></span><span class="MathJax" id="MathJax-Element-4-Frame" tabindex="0" data-mathml="&lt;math xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&quot;&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;E&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi&gt;z&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;/math&gt;" role="presentation" style="position: relative;"><nobr aria-hidden="true"><span class="math" id="MathJax-Span-150" style="width: 1.338em; display: inline-block;"><span style="display: inline-block; position: relative; width: 1.122em; height: 0px; font-size: 117%;"><span style="position: absolute; clip: rect(1.35em, 1001.12em, 2.508em, -1000em); top: -2.19em; left: 0em;"><span class="mrow" id="MathJax-Span-151"><span class="msubsup" id="MathJax-Span-152"><span style="display: inline-block; position: relative; width: 1.144em; height: 0px;"><span style="position: absolute; clip: rect(3.166em, 1000.76em, 4.167em, -1000em); top: -4.006em; left: 0em;"><span class="mi" id="MathJax-Span-153" style="font-family: MathJax_Math-italic;">E<span style="display: inline-block; overflow: hidden; height: 1px; width: 0.026em;"></span></span><span style="display: inline-block; width: 0px; height: 4.006em;"></span></span><span style="position: absolute; top: -3.856em; left: 0.738em;"><span class="mi" id="MathJax-Span-154" style="font-size: 70.7%; font-family: MathJax_Math-italic;">z<span style="display: inline-block; overflow: hidden; height: 1px; width: 0.002em;"></span></span><span style="display: inline-block; width: 0px; height: 4.006em;"></span></span></span></span></span><span style="display: inline-block; width: 0px; height: 2.19em;"></span></span></span><span style="display: inline-block; overflow: hidden; vertical-align: -0.247em; border-left: 0px solid; width: 0px; height: 1.105em;"></span></span></nobr><span class="MJX_Assistive_MathML" role="presentation"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mi>E</mi><mi>z</mi></msub></math></span></span>-polarized Gaussian source, create a list of <em>k</em> wavevectors that we want to compute Žē(k) over, and compute the associated frequencies by using the <code>k_points</code> function:</p>
<pre><code class="language-py hljs language-python">fcen = <span class="hljs-number">1.0</span>
df = <span class="hljs-number">2.0</span>

sources = [mp.Source(mp.GaussianSource(fcen, fwidth=df), component=mp.Ez, center=mp.Vector3())]

kmin = <span class="hljs-number">0.3</span>
kmax = <span class="hljs-number">2.2</span>
k_interp = <span class="hljs-number">99</span>

kpts = mp.interpolate(k_interp, [mp.Vector3(kmin), mp.Vector3(kmax)])

sim = mp.Simulation(cell_size=cell, geometry=[], sources=sources, default_material=default_material, resolution=resolution)

all_freqs = sim.run_k_points(<span class="hljs-number">200</span>, kpts)  <span class="hljs-comment"># a list of lists of frequencies</span>
</code></pre>
<p>The <code>run_k_points</code> function returns a <em>list of lists</em> of frequencies ŌĆö one list of complex frequencies for each <em>k</em> point ŌĆö which we store in the <code>all_freqs</code> variable. Finally, we want to loop over this list and print out the corresponding ╬Ą via the ratio (ck/Žē)<span class="MathJax_Preview" style="color: inherit; display: none;"></span><span class="MathJax" id="MathJax-Element-5-Frame" tabindex="0" data-mathml="&lt;math xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&quot;&gt;&lt;msup&gt;&lt;mi&gt;&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mn&gt;2&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/msup&gt;&lt;/math&gt;" role="presentation" style="position: relative;"><nobr aria-hidden="true"><span class="math" id="MathJax-Span-155" style="width: 0.537em; display: inline-block;"><span style="display: inline-block; position: relative; width: 0.427em; height: 0px; font-size: 117%;"><span style="position: absolute; clip: rect(1.196em, 1000.43em, 2.35em, -1000em); top: -2.19em; left: 0em;"><span class="mrow" id="MathJax-Span-156"><span class="msubsup" id="MathJax-Span-157"><span style="display: inline-block; position: relative; width: 0.429em; height: 0px;"><span style="position: absolute; clip: rect(3.846em, 1000em, 4.167em, -1000em); top: -4.006em; left: 0em;"><span class="mi" id="MathJax-Span-158"></span><span style="display: inline-block; width: 0px; height: 4.006em;"></span></span><span style="position: absolute; top: -4.369em; left: 0em;"><span class="mn" id="MathJax-Span-159" style="font-size: 70.7%; font-family: MathJax_Main;">2</span><span style="display: inline-block; width: 0px; height: 4.006em;"></span></span></span></span></span><span style="display: inline-block; width: 0px; height: 2.19em;"></span></span></span><span style="display: inline-block; overflow: hidden; vertical-align: -0.063em; border-left: 0px solid; width: 0px; height: 1.101em;"></span></span></nobr><span class="MJX_Assistive_MathML" role="presentation"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msup><mi></mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math></span></span> as described above. To do this, we will use Python's <code>zip</code> function which combines multiple lists into one:</p>
<pre><code class="language-py hljs language-python"><span class="hljs-keyword">for</span> fs, kx <span class="hljs-keyword">in</span> <span class="hljs-built_in">zip</span>(all_freqs, [v.x <span class="hljs-keyword">for</span> v <span class="hljs-keyword">in</span> kpts]):
    <span class="hljs-keyword">for</span> f <span class="hljs-keyword">in</span> fs:
            <span class="hljs-built_in">print</span>(<span class="hljs-string">"eps:, {.6f}, {.6f}, {.6f}"</span>.<span class="hljs-built_in">format</span>(f.real, f.imag, (kx / f)**<span class="hljs-number">2</span>))
</code></pre>
<p>Alternatively we could just read all of the frequencies into Python or Octave/Matlab and compute the ratios there. After running the program with</p>
<pre><code class="language-sh hljs language-bash">unix% python -u material-dispersion.py | <span class="hljs-built_in">tee</span> material-dispersion.out
</code></pre>
<p>we can then <code>grep</code> for the frequencies and the computed dielectric function, and plot it. First, let's plot the dispersion relation Žē(k) for the real part of Žē:</p>
<p><img alt="" src="https://meep.readthedocs.io/en/master/images/Material-dispersion-bands.png#center"></p>
<p>The red circles are the computed points from Meep, whereas the blue line is the analytical band diagram from the specified ╬Ą(Žē). As you can see, we get <em>two</em> bands at each <em>k</em>, separated by a polaritonic gap (shaded yellow). This dispersion relation can be thought of as the interaction (anti-crossing) between the light line of the ambient ╬Ą=2.25 material (dashed black line) and the horizontal line corresponding to the phonon resonance.</p>
<p>Similarly, the computed and analytical real parts of the dielectric function are given by:</p>
<p><img alt="" src="https://meep.readthedocs.io/en/master/images/Material-dispersion-epsre.png#center"></p>
<p>which shows excellent agreement between the analytical (blue line) and numerical (red circles) calculations. The imaginary part, however, is more subtle:</p>
<p><img alt="" src="https://meep.readthedocs.io/en/master/images/Material-dispersion-epsim.png#center"></p>
<p>The blue line is the analytical calculation from above and the red circles are the numerical value from Meep ŌĆö why is the agreement so poor? There is nothing wrong with Meep, and this is <em>not</em> a numerical error. The problem is simply that we are comparing apples and oranges.</p>
<p>The blue line is the analytical calculation of ╬Ą(Žē) for a <em>real</em> frequency Žē which corresponds to solutions with a <em>complex</em> wavevector <em>k</em>, whereas Meep is computing ╬Ą at a <em>complex</em> Žē for a <em>real</em> wavevector <em>k</em>. So, the correct comparison is to plug Meep's <em>complex</em> Žē into the analytical formula for ╬Ą(Žē), which results in the green lines on the graph that fall almost on top of the red circles.</p>
<p>Why did our comparison of the <em>real</em> part of ╬Ą look so good, then? The reason is that ╬Ą(Žē) at real and complex values of Žē are closely related by the analytic properties of ╬Ą. In particular, because ╬Ą is an analytic function on the real-Žē axis, adding a <em>small</em> imaginary part to Žē as we are doing here does not change ╬Ą by much. The losses are small for all of the computed <em>k</em> points. The change was only significant for the imaginary ╬Ą because the imaginary ╬Ą was small to begin with.</p>
              
